@width 72

@node main "Readme_amiga.guide"

Readme - Amiga

On the same day that I uploaded version 1 release 12 to the Aminet, the
author (Angus Duggan) informed me that release 16 was available!

  @{" Where I found the sources          " link "Source"}

  @{" ...and what I did with the sources " link "Compiler"}

  @{" Requirements                       " link "Reqs"}

Why?  - pstops is a very useful program, allowing you to print several
        postscript pages on the one page after the postscript file
        has been generated by a program e.g. TeX's dvips.

        In fact, people have written pages about pstops on the
        world-wide web!

Bugs? - except for pstops and epsffit, all the other programs do not print
        out their help line when no argument is given.  I do not know why.
        Try, for example, `psnup -?', if you want see the help lines
        of the other programs.

      - I have only really tested psnup to any extent.  I have not
        tested epsffit at all.  I do not really know what psbook is
        supposed to do.

  The original @{" readme " link readme/MAIN } and @{" LICENSE " link LICENSE/MAIN }.

Some Amigaguide files are provided.

  @{" psbook   " link psbook.guide/MAIN } - rearranges pages into signatures
  @{" psnup    " link psnup.guide/MAIN } - put multiple pages per physical sheet of paper
  @{" psresize " link psresize.guide/MAIN } - alter document paper size
  @{" psselect " link psselect.guide/MAIN } - selects pages and page ranges
  @{" pstops   " link pstops.guide/MAIN } - performs general page rearrangement and selection
  @{" epsffit  " link epsffit.guide/MAIN} - fits an EPSF file to a given bounding box

Address - E-mail   : vkelim@ariel.unimelb.edu.au
          Homepage : http://ariel.unimelb.edu.au/~vkelim/ (non-interactive)

David Fong

@endnode

@node "Source" "Where I found the sources"

`The definitive archive site for PSUtils updates is ftp.dcs.ed.ac.uk, in the
 directory pub/ajcd/. The latest version will be in psutils.tar.Z, older
 versions may also be in psutils-*.tar.Z'

Also try the web page...

http://www.dcs.ed.ac.uk/home/ajcd/psutils/

At first, I had obtained the source from CTAN archives (TeX archives)

e.g. ftp.cs.rmit.edu /tex-archive/support/
     ftp.dante.de

@endnode

@node "Compiler" "What I did with the sources"

Compiled with gcc 2.7.2 (still in beta version), with libnix v1.1

Changes I had made...

I changed config.h (the original config is `config_old.h').  I defined
TMPDIR as "ram:t", this assumes that t: is in fact assigned to ram:t.
I did not want to define TMPDIR as "t:", because I did not know if
any of the utilities would try to add a `/' to TMPDIR.  In fact, I do
not know if TMPDIR is used at all; none of pstops.c psutil.c pserror.c
psspec.c (and their respective *.h files) make any reference to TMPDIR.

Unlike my previous release, I have now defined PAPER (the default
paper size) to be a4.

I changed only line in pstops.c, so that pstops.c will report what
the default paper size is (if no arguments are given in the command
line).

I did not use the make files.  I have trouble getting my `make' working,
I am not really a C programmer!

@endnode

@node "Reqs" "Requirements"

I compiled the sources with libnix v1.1, so...

The provided programs no longer requires ixemul.library!

@endnode

